  text='Before the death in 1817 of George Lord Dy, the widow of the man who had married Wordsworth\'s brother, Lord Grey officially offered Wordsworth the post of Stamp Distributor at the Stamp Office, with a salary of £500 per annum, and a house within the precincts of the Office. However, it was discovered that a man employed under Lord Grey embezzled revenues from the post, and so Grey kept it secret, while allowing Wordsworth the income and emoluments of the office. Lord John Russell wrote in his memoirs of the Stamp Office: "The appointment was not put into effect, and superannuation was paid for a successor. This superannuation avoided any repayment beyond the grave for the post being of a sinecure for political reasons as better than patronage of jobs. The Treasury Department admitted that he was coerced into this action by a system of private agreements to the previous incumbent". According to Edward Mangan in his book on Romantic poet Wordsworth and his colleagues, "the appointment might have worked very well, even though it was against public sentiment, had Wordsworth been wiser than he was."'
